→ VT2 assessment conducted = can now establish 3-zone personalized model

2) HR ZONES (Javier):
• Zone 1: <135 bpm (below VT1)
• Zone 2: 135–155 bpm (VT1 to VT2)
• Zone 3: >155 bpm (above VT2)

8-WEEK BLOCK OVERVIEW:
Wks 1–2: Build endurance (45 min Z1 steady + 50 min Z2 steady + 70 min LSD on weekend)
Wks 3–4: Threshold intervals (8 min Z2 + 2 min Z1 recovery × 3 sets; LSD 80 min)
Wks 5–6: Extend threshold (10–12 min Z2 × 3 sets; LSD 90 min — simulates race pacing)
Wk 7: Taper (40–50% volume reduction; short intervals to stay sharp)
Wk 8: Race week (20–30 min easy Z1 spins Mon–Thu; rest Fri; RACE Sat)

3) BLACK HOLE ZONE NAVIGATION IN RACE:
Zone 2 = "hard enough to fatigue, not hard enough for maximal adaptation"
Problem in 100-mile event: Unsustainable at zone 2 for 6–8 hours → glycogen depletion, DNF risk

RACE PACING STRATEGY:
• Miles 1–50: Zone 1 (HR <135, conversational, conserve glycogen)
• Miles 50–80: Shift to Zone 2 (HR 140–150) — body adapted to saddle time, build push
• Miles 80–100: Zone 1–2 alternating — finishing strong without overcooking final 20 miles
Avoid: Sustained Zone 2 from start = hitting wall by mile 60

4) OVERTRAINING PREVENTION via ZONE 1 DISTRIBUTION:
• ~40% training time in Zone 1 (recovery rides, warm-ups, cool-downs)
• Recovery day after every Zone 2/3 session
• Monitor RHR: >5 bpm rise from 58 bpm baseline = add rest day
• Recovery HR check: Should drop 20–30 bpm within 1 min post-exercise; slower = fatigue
• 10% weekly volume rule: Never exceed 10% total load increase week-over-week`
